# Doc heading emoji: fixed palette only

PyDevices docs use a small, fixed set of emoji as landmarks on section
headings across repos (`pydisplay`, `cmods` and its native cmods, org
`.github`, etc.). The canonical palette lives in
[`.github/CONTRIBUTING.md`](https://github.com/PyDevices/.github/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#doc-style-emoji)
(local clone: `dotgithub/CONTRIBUTING.md`) — read it there rather than
duplicating the table here, since this rule would drift out of sync
otherwise.

## When writing or editing docs

- If you add a heading that matches one of the palette's meanings (getting
  started/install/build, examples/demos, getting help, reporting bugs,
  contributing, documentation/reference links, troubleshooting/warnings),
  use that heading's emoji — don't leave it plain just because it's new.
- Don't invent an eighth emoji, and don't reuse one of the seven for a
  meaning it doesn't already have.
- Don't add an emoji to a heading that doesn't genuinely match one of the
  seven meanings, and don't create a new section just to have somewhere to
  put one.
- If a doc has several parallel/alternative headings for the same category
  (e.g. two different "Build" methods), leave them plain rather than
  tagging one arbitrarily — see the "rules of thumb" in
  `.github/CONTRIBUTING.md` for why.
- Nav/sidebar labels (e.g. `mkdocs.yml` `nav:` entries) are declared
  separately from in-page headings in this org's docs — the emoji goes on
  the in-page `#`/`##` heading, not into nav config.

## If the palette needs to change

Editing the palette itself (adding/removing an emoji, changing a meaning)
is a real decision, not routine doc maintenance — propose it and update
`.github/CONTRIBUTING.md` first, then re-sweep existing docs for
consistency rather than letting old and new meanings coexist.
